# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: atmospheric-pressure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/adiabatic-process] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] In the fields of physics, engineering, and earth sciences, **advection** is the transport of a substance or quantity by bulk motion of a fluid.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] The properties of that substance are carried with it.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Generally the majority of the advected substance is also a fluid.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] The properties that are carried with the advected substance are conserved properties such as energy.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] An example of advection is the transport of pollutants or silt in a river by bulk water flow downstream.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Another commonly advected quantity is energy or enthalpy.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Here the fluid may be any material that contains thermal energy, such as water or air.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] In general, any substance or conserved extensive quantity can be advected by a fluid that can hold or contain the quantity or substance.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] During advection, a fluid transports some conserved quantity or material via bulk motion.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] The fluid's motion is described mathematically as a vector field, and the transported material is described by a scalar field showing its distribution over space.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Advection requires currents in the fluid, and so cannot happen in rigid solids.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] It does not include transport of substances by molecular diffusion.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Advection is sometimes confused with the more encompassing process of convection, which is the combination of advective transport and diffusive transport.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] In meteorology it is the transfer by the wind of an atmospheric mass.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Advection is important for the formation of orographic clouds and the precipitation of water from clouds, as part of the hydrological cycle.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] The **advection equation** is a first-order hyperbolic partial differential equation that governs the motion of a conserved scalar field as it is advected by a known velocity vector field.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] It is derived using the scalar field's conservation law, together with Gauss's theorem, and taking the infinitesimal limit.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] One easily visualized example of advection is the transport of ink dumped into a river.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] As the river flows, ink will move downstream in a "pulse" via advection, as the water's movement itself transports the ink.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] If added to a lake without significant bulk water flow, the ink would simply disperse outwards from its source in a diffusive manner, which is not advection.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Note that as it moves downstream, the "pulse" of ink will also spread via diffusion.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] The sum of these processes is called convection.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] In particular, if the flow is steady, then ${\mathbf {u} }\cdot \nabla \psi =0,$ which shows that $\psi$ is constant (because ${\textstyle \nabla \psi =0}$ for any vector ${\textstyle \mathbf {u} }$ ) along a streamline.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Here, $\mathbf {a}$ is a vector field instead of the scalar field $\psi$ .
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Solutions to the advection equation can be approximated using numerical methods, where interest typically centers on discontinuous "shock" solutions and necessary conditions for convergence (e.g. the CFL condition).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Since skew symmetry implies only imaginary eigenvalues, this form reduces the "blow up" and "spectral blocking" often experienced in numerical solutions with sharp discontinuities.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] The term *advection* often serves as a synonym for *convection*, and this correspondence of terms is used in the literature.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] More technically, convection applies to the movement of a fluid (often due to density gradients created by thermal gradients), whereas advection is the movement of some material by the velocity of the fluid.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Thus, although it might seem confusing, it is technically correct to think of momentum being advected by the velocity field in the Navier-Stokes equations, although the resulting motion would be considered to be convection.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Because of the specific use of the term convection to indicate transport in association with thermal gradients, it is probably safer to use the term advection if one is uncertain about which terminology best describes their particular system.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] In meteorology and physical oceanography, advection often refers to the horizontal transport of some property of the atmosphere or ocean, such as heat, humidity or salinity, and convection generally refers to vertical transport (vertical advection).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] Advection is important for the formation of orographic clouds (terrain-forced convection) and the precipitation of water from clouds, as part of the hydrological cycle.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/advection] The advection equation also applies if the quantity being advected is represented by a probability density function at each point, although accounting for diffusion is more difficult.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter-setting] The setting of a sensitive pressure altimeter is shown in the Kollsman window.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter-setting] The QNH altimeter setting is one of the data included in METAR messages.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter-setting] QNH and QFE are arbitrary Q codes rather than abbreviations, but the mnemonics "nautical height" (for QNH) and "field elevation" (for QFE) are often used by pilots to distinguish between them.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter-setting] QNH and QFE will have errors when not at station elevation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter-setting] QFF is aerodrome pressure (QNH) reduced to sea level.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter-setting] It is designed to read zero at sea level in the vicinity of the aerodrome, unlike QNH which will not read precisely zero at sea-level.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] An **altimeter**, or **altitude meter**, is an instrument used to measure the altitude of an object relative to a fixed level.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] The measurement of altitude is called **altimetry**, which is related to the term bathymetry, the measurement of depth under water.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] Altitude can be determined by the measurement of atmospheric pressure.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] The greater the altitude, the lower the pressure.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] When a barometer is supplied with a nonlinear calibration so as to indicate altitude, the instrument is a type of altimeter called a pressure altimeter or barometric altimeter.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] A pressure altimeter is the altimeter found in most aircraft, and skydivers use wrist-mounted versions for similar purposes.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] Hikers and mountain climbers use wrist-mounted or hand-held altimeters, in addition to other navigational tools such as maps, magnetic compasses, and receivers for global navigation satellite systems (GNSS), such as GPS.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] In 1931, the US Army Air corps and General Electric together tested a **sonic altimeter** for aircraft, which was considered more reliable and accurate than one that relied on air pressure when heavy fog or rain was present.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] The new altimeter used a series of high-pitched sounds like those made by a bat to measure the distance from the aircraft to the surface, which on return to the aircraft was converted to feet shown on a gauge inside the aircraft cockpit.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] A radar altimeter measures altitude more directly, using the time taken for a radio signal to reflect from the surface back to the aircraft.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] Alternatively, Frequency Modulated Continuous-wave radar can be used.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] The greater the frequency shift the further the distance travelled.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] This method can achieve much better accuracy than the pulsed radar for the same outlay and radar altimeters that use frequency modulation are industry standard.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] The radar altimeter is used to measure height above ground level during landing in commercial and military aircraft.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] Radar altimeters are also a component of terrain avoidance warning systems, warning the pilot if the aircraft is flying too low, or if there is rising terrain ahead.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] Radar altimeter technology is also used in terrain-following radar allowing combat aircraft to fly at very low height above the terrain.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] After extensive research and experimentation, it has been shown that "phase radio-altimeters" are most suitable for ground effect vehicles, as compared to laser, isotropic or ultrasonic altimeters.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] Lidar technology is used to help navigate the helicopter Ingenuity on its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars by means of a downward-facing Lidar altimeter.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] Satellite navigation receivers like those used with the Global Positioning System (GPS) can also determine altitude by trilateration with four or more satellites.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] In aircraft, altitude determined using autonomous GPS is not reliable enough to supersede the pressure altimeter without using some method of augmentation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/altimeter] In hiking and climbing, it is common to find that the altitude measured by GPS is off by as much as 400 feet (122 metres) depending on satellite orientation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] The **Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory** (**AOML**), a federal research laboratory, is part of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's (NOAA) Office of Oceanic and Atmospheric Research (OAR), located in Miami in the United States.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] AOML's research spans tropical cyclone and hurricanes, coastal ecosystems, oceans and human health, climate studies, global carbon systems, and ocean observations.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] It is one of seven NOAA Research Laboratories (RLs).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] AOML's organizational structure consists of an Office of the Director and three scientific research divisions.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] The Office of the Director oversees the Laboratory's scientific programs, as well as its financial, administrative, computer, outreach/education, and facility management services.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] Research programs are augmented by Cooperative Institutes, such as the Cooperative Institute for Marine and Atmospheric Studies (CIMAS), a joint enterprise with the University of Miami’s Rosenstiel School of Marine, Atmospheric, and Earth Science.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] CIMAS enables AOML and university scientists to collaborate on research areas of mutual interest and facilitates the participation of students and visiting scientists.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] The Laboratory is a member of a unique community of marine research and educational institutions located on Virginia Key in Miami, Florida.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] Approximately $150M per year is invested in marine science and education among the University of Miami's Rosenstiel School of Marine, Atmospheric, and Earth Science, NOAA's Southeast Fisheries Science Center, the Miami Seaquarium, the Maritime and Science Technology Academy (MAST Academy).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] The deeper roots of AOML can be traced to the oceanographic investigations of the United States Coast Survey beginning in the mid-19th century under the direction of Professor Alexander Dallas Bache, great-grandson of Benjamin Franklin and a preeminent U.S. science figure of the age.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] In subsequent decades, the urgency of charting coastal waters in support of growing commerce, a task increased by the acquisition of Alaska, Hawaii, and other island territories, came to require all the resources of the Coast Survey.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] The modern era can be considered to have begun during the 1960s.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] In early 1966, an Institute for Oceanography was created, primarily from research groups of the then-United States Coast and Geodetic Survey, which at the time was a part of the Environmental Science Services Administration (ESSA), the forerunner of NOAA).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] The following year the institute was relocated to Miami for a variety of reasons, including the presence already in Miami of meteorological research groups of ESSA dedicated to hurricane research, and air-sea interaction was a hot topic of the time in weather research.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] All of these groups were reorganized as the Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratories (AOML) and by 1973 took occupancy in the new laboratory constructed on Virginia Key.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] New projects include expansion of the use of satellite and locally operated remote sensing techniques to enhance the coverage and detail of observations.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] Outreach via electronic communication is enabling AOML to serve a larger constituency with access to oceanographic and meteorological observations.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] AOML conducts research that seeks to understand the physical, chemical, and biological characteristics and processes of the ocean and atmosphere, both separately and as a coupled system.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] The Laboratory's research themes (oceans and climate, coastal ecosystems, and hurricanes and tropical meteorology) employ a cross-disciplinary approach, conducted through collaborative interactions with national and international research and environmental forecasting institutions.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] AOML carries out interdisciplinary scientific investigations of the physics of ocean currents and water properties, and on the role of the ocean in climate, extreme weather events, and ecosystems.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] The tools used to carry out these studies range from sensors on deep ocean moorings to satellite-based instruments to measurements made on research and commercial shipping vessels and autonomous vehicles, and include data analysis and numerical modeling as well as theoretical approaches.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] Coastal and regional ecosystem research has been a focus of AOML activities for more than two decades.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] Tropical meteorology research at AOML is focused on advancing the understanding and prediction of hurricanes and other tropical weather.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atlantic-oceanographic-and-meteorological-laboratory] Scientists conduct their research utilizing a combination of models, theories, and observations, with particular emphasis on data obtained with research aircraft in the inner core of tropical cyclones and their surrounding environment.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] O2 showed major variations during the Proterozoic, including a billion-year period of euxinia, until reaching a steady state of more than 15% by the end of the Precambrian.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The amount of oxygen in the atmosphere has fluctuated over the last 600 million years, reaching a peak of about 35% around 280 million years ago during the Carboniferous period, significantly higher than today's 21%.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Two main processes govern changes in the atmosphere: the evolution of plants and their increasing role in carbon fixation, and the consumption of oxygen by rapidly diversifying animal faunae and also by plants for photorespiration and their own metabolic needs at night.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Breakdown of pyrite and volcanic eruptions release sulfur into the atmosphere, which reacts and hence reduces oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] However, volcanic eruptions also release carbon dioxide, which can fuel oxygenic photosynthesis by terrestrial and aquatic plants.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] The cause of the variation of the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere is not precisely understood.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Periods with more oxygen in the atmosphere were often associated with more rapid development of animals.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Since 1750, human activity, especially after the Industrial Revolution, has increased the concentrations of various greenhouse gases, most importantly carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] Greenhouse gas emissions, coupled with deforestation and destruction of wetlands via logging and land developments, have caused an observed rise in global temperatures, with the global average surface temperatures being 1.1 °C higher in the 2011–2020 decade than they were in 1850.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-of-earth] It has raised concerns of man-made climate change, which can have significant environmental impacts such as sea level rise, ocean acidification, glacial retreat (which threatens water security), increasing extreme weather events and wildfires, ecological collapse and mass dying of wildlife.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-unit] The **standard atmosphere** (symbol: **atm**) is a unit of pressure defined as 101325 Pa.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-unit] It is sometimes used as a *reference pressure* or *standard pressure*.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-unit] It is approximately equal to Earth's average atmospheric pressure at sea level.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-unit] The standard atmosphere was originally defined as the pressure exerted by a 760 mm column of mercury at 0 °C (32 °F) and standard gravity (*g*n = 9.80665 m/s2).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-unit] It was used as a reference condition for physical and chemical properties, and the definition of the centigrade temperature scale set 100 °C as the boiling point of water at this pressure.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-unit] In 1954, the 10th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) adopted *standard atmosphere* for general use and affirmed its definition of being precisely equal to 1013250 dynes per square centimetre (101325 Pa).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-unit] This defined pressure in a way that is independent of the properties of any particular substance.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmosphere-unit] The notation **ata** has been used to indicate an absolute pressure measured in either standard atmospheres (atm) or technical atmospheres (at).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] In most circumstances, atmospheric pressure is closely approximated by the hydrostatic pressure caused by the weight of air above the measurement point.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] As elevation increases, there is less overlying atmospheric mass, so atmospheric pressure decreases with increasing elevation.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Because the atmosphere is thin relative to the Earth's radius – especially the dense atmospheric layer at low altitudes – the Earth's gravitational acceleration as a function of altitude can be approximated as constant and contributes little to this fall-off.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure measures force per unit area, with SI units of pascals (1 pascal = 1 newton per square meter, 1 N/m2).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] A column of air with a cross-sectional area of 1 in2 would have a weight of about 14.7 lbf, resulting in a pressure of 14.7 lbf/in2.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is caused by the gravitational attraction of the planet on the atmospheric gases above the surface and is a function of the mass of the planet, the radius of the surface, and the amount and composition of the gases and their vertical distribution in the atmosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] It is modified by the planetary rotation and local effects such as wind velocity, density variations due to temperature and variations in composition.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The *mean sea-level pressure* (MSLP) is the atmospheric pressure at mean sea level.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] This is the atmospheric pressure normally given in weather reports via meteorologists on radio, television, and newspapers or on the Internet.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The *altimeter setting* in aviation is an atmospheric pressure adjustment.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] In aviation weather reports (METAR), QNH is transmitted around the world in hectopascals or millibars (1 hectopascal = 1 millibar).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] In the United States, Canada, and Japan altimeter setting is reported in inches of mercury (to two decimal places).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The United States and Canada also report *sea-level pressure* SLP, which is adjusted to sea level by a different method, in the remarks section, not in the internationally transmitted part of the code, in hectopascals or millibars.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] However, in Canada's public weather reports, sea level pressure is instead reported in kilopascals.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] In the US weather code remarks, three digits are all that are transmitted; decimal points and the one or two most significant digits are omitted: 1,013.2 hPa (14.695 psi) is transmitted as 132; 1,000 hPa (100 kPa) is transmitted as 000; 998.7 hPa is transmitted as 987; etc.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] A system transmitting the last three digits transmits the same code (800) for 1080.0 hPa as for 980.0 hPa.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The highest *sea-level pressure* on Earth occurs in Siberia, where the Siberian High often attains a *sea-level pressure* above 1,050 hPa (15.2 psi; 31 inHg), with record highs close to 1,085 hPa (15.74 psi; 32.0 inHg).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The lowest measurable *sea-level pressure* is found at the centres of tropical cyclones and tornadoes, with a record low of 870 hPa (12.6 psi; 26 inHg).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] For numerical reasons, atmospheric models such as general circulation models (GCMs) usually predict the nondimensional *logarithm of surface pressure*.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The average value of surface pressure on Earth is 985 hPa.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] This is in contrast to mean sea-level pressure, which involves the extrapolation of pressure to sea level for locations above or below sea level.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The average pressure at mean sea level (MSL) in the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) is 1,013.25 hPa, or 1 atmosphere (atm), or 29.92 inches of mercury.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure (P), mass (m), and acceleration due to gravity (g) are related by P = F/A = (m*g)/A, where A is the surface area.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure is thus proportional to the weight per unit area of the atmospheric mass above that location.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure on Earth varies with the altitude of the surface, so air pressure on mountains is usually lower than air pressure at sea level.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure varies smoothly from the Earth's surface to the top of the mesosphere.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Although the pressure changes with the weather, NASA has averaged the conditions for all parts of the earth year-round.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] As altitude increases, atmospheric pressure decreases.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] One can calculate the atmospheric pressure at a given altitude.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Temperature and humidity also affect the atmospheric pressure.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Pressure is proportional to temperature and inversely related to humidity, and both of these are necessary to compute an accurate figure.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The graph on the rightabove was developed for a temperature of 15 °C and a relative humidity of 0%.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] At low altitudes above sea level, the pressure decreases by about 1.2 kPa (12 hPa) for every 100 meters.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric pressure varies widely on Earth, and differences in pressure are important in studying weather and climate.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Some variations in pressure are very regular.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] One important source of variation is atmospheric tides.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Atmospheric tides are strongest in tropical zones, with an amplitude of a few hectopascals, and almost zero in polar areas.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Tropical tidal variations in pressure consist principally of two superimposed harmonics – a circadian (24 h) cycle and a semi-circadian (12 h) cycle.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded on Earth above 750 meters was 1,084.8 hPa (32.03 inHg; 1.0706 atm), measured in Tosontsengel, Mongolia on 19 December 2001.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The highest adjusted-to-sea level barometric pressure ever recorded below 750 meters was at Agata, in Evenk Autonomous Okrug, Russia (66°53' N, 93°28' E, elevation: 261 m, 856 ft), on 31 December 1968 of 1,083.8 hPa (32.005 inHg).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The Dead Sea, the lowest sea surface on Earth, at 430 metres (1,410 ft) below sea level, has a correspondingly high typical atmospheric pressure of 1,065 hPa.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] A below-sea-level surface pressure record of 1,081.8 hPa (31.95 inHg; 1.0677 atm) was set on 21 February 1961.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The lowest non-tornadic atmospheric pressure ever measured was 870 hPa (26 inHg; 0.86 atm), set on 12 October 1979, during Typhoon Tip in the western Pacific Ocean.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The measurement was based on an instrumental observation made from a reconnaissance aircraft.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] One atmosphere (101.325 kPa or 14.7 psi) is also the pressure caused by the weight of a column of freshwater of approximately 10.3 m (33.8 ft).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Thus, a diver 10.3 m under water experiences a pressure of about 2 atmospheres (1 atm of air plus 1 atm of water).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Conversely, 10.3 m is the maximum height to which water can be raised using suction under standard atmospheric conditions.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Low pressures, such as natural gas lines, are sometimes specified in inches of water, typically written as *w.c.* (water column) gauge or *w.g.* (inches water) gauge.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] A typical gas-using residential appliance in the US is rated for a maximum of 1⁄2 psi (3.4 kPa; 34 mbar), which is approximately 14 w.g.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Similar metric units with a wide variety of names and notation based on millimeters, centimeters or meters are now less commonly used.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Pure water boils at 100 °C (212 °F) at Earth's standard atmospheric pressure.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] The boiling point is the temperature at which the vapour pressure is equal to the atmospheric pressure around the liquid.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Because of this, the boiling point of liquids is lower at lower pressure and higher at higher pressure.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Cooking at high elevations, therefore, requires adjustments to recipes or pressure cooking.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] A rough approximation of elevation can be obtained by measuring the temperature at which water boils; in the mid-19th century, this method was used by explorers.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] Conversely, if one wishes to evaporate a liquid at a lower temperature, for example in distillation, the atmospheric pressure may be lowered by using a vacuum pump, as in a rotary evaporator.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] An important application of the knowledge that atmospheric pressure varies directly with altitude was in determining the height of hills and mountains, thanks to reliable pressure measurement devices.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] In 1774, Nevil Maskelyne was confirming Newton's theory of gravitation at and on Schiehallion mountain in Scotland, and he needed to measure elevations on the mountain's sides accurately.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] This event is known as the Schiehallion experiment.
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] William Roy, using barometric pressure, was able to confirm Maskelyne's height determinations; the agreement was within one meter (3.28 feet).
[src:atmospheric-pressure/atmospheric-pressure] This method became and continues to be useful for survey work and map making.
